{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472613"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1549"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1549"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.17,0.19,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1549"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16356"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"5841"},{"type":"tags","id":"6022"},{"type":"tags","id":"6023"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2564"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy sustains a swollen right thumb after a fight. He presents to the emergency department approximately four hours after the fight, with ongoing pain. He recounts a history of excessive adduction of the thumb during the encounter. On examination, pain limits his ability to adduct his thumb, but he is able to abduct, extend, flex and oppose his thumb with relative ease. His right radial pulse is bounding and regular, and his sensation remains grossly in tact in the distributions of the radial, ulnar and median nerves. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following injuries does his X-ray show?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Avulsion fracture of the radial aspect proximal phalanx","Gamekeeper\u0027s thumb","Salter-Harris type II fracture at the base of the proximal phalanx","Dislocation of the metacarpal-phalangeal joint","Dislocation of the metacarpal-carpal joint"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows an \u003Cstrong\u003Eavulsion fracture at the radial side of the proximal phalanx\u003C/strong\u003E, as a result of injury to the radial collateral ligament. There also appears to be a loose body on the ulnar side. Had the avulsion fracture been on the ulnar side of the proximal phalanx, it could be called a \u201cgamekeeper\u2019s thumb\u201d, which is a chronic instability of the metacarpal phalangeal joint following ulnar collateral ligament damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis boy had a thumb spica cast applied and was referred to the orthopaedic hand clinic for follow-up. Instability of the metacarpal phalangeal joint is an important complication to monitor. There is no evidence of dislocation in the X-ray.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-displaced phalangeal fractures are best treated by external splintage."],"references":["Patel, S, Potty, A, Taylor, EJ \u0026 Sorene, ED 2010, \u2018Collateral ligament injuries of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the thumb: a treatment algorithm\u2019, Strategies in Trauma and Limb Reconstruction, vol. 5, no. 1, pp. 1\u201310.","Avery, DM, Inkellis, ER \u0026 Carlson, MG 2017, \u2018Thumb collateral ligament injuries in the athlete\u2019, Current Reviews in Musculoskeletal Medicine, vol. 10, no. 1, pp. 28\u201337."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16356"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18371"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18371"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/659e6201-7c99-4dc5-9a48-a7f35180da31.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/659e6201-7c99-4dc5-9a48-a7f35180da31.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":332,"height":795}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16356"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-11-29T07:48:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-11-29T07:48:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1549"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou